Basics

Before proceeding to the specific aspects of the course; let’s first talk about a few basics about programming in R.

Packages

Throughout the course we will be using a standard suite of packages (additional functions which provide additional analytical capabilities). In order to ensure that you have all required functionality for the course, be sure that each RMarkdown file you write has the following block at the top, which should not be altered:

source("https://github.com/reyesem/reyesem.github.io/raw/master/files/MA483/MA483Setup.R")

Anatomy of RMarkdown File

An RMarkdown file is comprised of two components: basic text and “code chunks” which perform the analysis. When the document is compiled (“knit”) the code is evaluated and the results added seemlessly into your document. This encourages a reproducible workflow (someone can recreate all your results should the data change).

Code blocks can be added using the “Insert” button at the top of the script window. Code blocks have the following form:

```{r}
Code goes here...
```

Notice that the code blocks always begin and end with the triple backticks (found on your keyboard in the upper-left-hand corner with the tilde).

Anatomy of R Code

Most code chunks all look the same. Below is a very simple code chunk. Objects are “assigned” to an object using an equal sign (or arrow <-). The code essentially says that the thing on the left will contain anything generated on the right.

# Comments (not evaluated) begin with a hashtag.
ObjectName <- code to generate results

Just typing the name of an object prints that object out; that output, in turn, will appear in your final document.

If we want to do something to that object, we will make use of the “pipe operator” (%>%) which essentially says take the thing before and use it in the next function. For example, we might summarise an object as follows:

ObjectTwo <- ObjectOne %>%
  summarise()

This code says take the thing called “ObjectOne” and “pipe it into” (use within) the summarise function; whatever the result of this operation is will be called “ObjectTwo.”

Creating a Dataset from Scratch

Occasionally, you may need to input data manually (generally, data will be provided to you). This is done using the tibble() function. Things to keep in mind include

  • Variables are separated by commas.
  • Each variable must be named (Variable_Name =).
  • Values are separated by commas and placed inside the c() function.
  • Values of a categorical variable are placed inside quotes.

Here is a hypothetical example in which the results of a simple survey are entered into a dataset called demographics.

demographics <- tibble(
  `Hair Color` = c("Black", "Black", "Brown", "Blonde", "Black"),
  Age = c(20, 19, 21, 20, 20)
)

Data Manipulation

Data is rarely perfect when we first obtain it. Often times, we will need to make changes. There are a few tasks which are performed regularly; these can generally be accomplished with the following two functions:

  • mutate(): manipulate variables or make transformations.
  • arrange(): sort a dataset.
  • filter(): subset the data based on some criteria.

mutate(): creating or changing variables

As an example, while the US measures fuel efficiency in miles per gallon, other countries often report the gallons required for a single mile. This new variable Gallons_per_Mile can be created using mutate():

mtcars <- mtcars %>%
  mutate(Gallons_per_Mile = 1/mpg)

Notice that we use the pipe operator (%>%) here; this essentially says take the dataset mtcars and feed it into the mutate() function. The mutate() function itself uses the notation New_Variable_Name = transformation of stuff. In this case, we create a new variable within the dataset mtcars. The result is stored within a dataset called mtcars (since that is on the left of the equal sign), essentially overwriting the original dataset.

The first few records of this dataset are shown below:

arrange(): order the data

To sort the data, consider ordering the mtcars dataset by the the number of cylinders the car has. This can be done using the arrange() function:

mtcars <- mtcars %>%
  arrange(cyl)

The results are stored in the mtcars dataset (the first few records of which are shown below).

filter(): subsetting a variable

If we only want to look at a subset of the data, we use the filter() function. For example, suppose we only want to consider vehicles which have automatic transmissions. Further, we would like to store those in a new dataset called automatic.only, we use the following code:

automatic.only <- mtcars %>%
  filter(am == 0)

When making comparisons, == is asking “are you equal?” We keep the records for which we would anser “yes” to this question. The original mtcars dataset is not altered; it remains unchanged. Instead, we have taken it, filtered it down, and then stored the results in automatic.only (the first few records of which are shown below).

recode(): Changing the values of a variable

When we work with categorical variables, we often want the values (or group labels) to be something readable. In order to do this, we may need to recode the data. Consider the variable am (transmission type). It is currently a 0/1 variable, and it is not obvious that 1 represents manual transmission and 0 automatic transmission. We can make this clearer by mutating the dataset and recoding that variable.

mtcars <- mtcars %>%
  mutate(am = recode(am, 
                     `0` = "automatic",
                     `1` = "manual"))

There is a difference between backticks \`` and single quotes’`. In the above, the backticks are used because we are converting a number into a phrase. The first few records of the updated dataset are shown below:

mpg cyl disp hp drat wt qsec vs am gear carb Gallons_per_Mile
22.8 4 108.0 93 3.85 2.320 18.61 1 manual 4 1 0.044
24.4 4 146.7 62 3.69 3.190 20.00 1 automatic 4 2 0.041
22.8 4 140.8 95 3.92 3.150 22.90 1 automatic 4 2 0.044
32.4 4 78.7 66 4.08 2.200 19.47 1 manual 4 1 0.031
30.4 4 75.7 52 4.93 1.615 18.52 1 manual 4 2 0.033
33.9 4 71.1 65 4.22 1.835 19.90 1 manual 4 1 0.029

If we now wanted to go further and change “automatic” to “Automatic Transmission”, we could recode again; this time, since the variable is already a phrase, we do not use backticks.

mtcars <- mtcars %>%
  mutate(am = recode(am, 
                     "automatic" = "Automatic Transmission",
                     "manual" = "Manual Transmission"))

If your dataset has groups coded as numbers (like above when 0 = automatic and 1 = manual), it is best to recode in order for graphics and models to work appropriately.

The resulting output is divided up by the type of variables in the dataset. Categorical variables (“characters” and “factors” in R) are summarized differently (counts of each unique value) than numeric variables (mean, percentiles, etc.).

mtcars %>%

Graphics

A picture is worth 1000 words. A good graphical summary of the data should not only be a first step in an analysis, but it should also accompany any good analysis to help convey the message of the data. All graphics in this class will be produced with the qplot() function. If you are interested in moving beyond what is described here, I would encourage you to look at the ggplot2 package and would guide you toward the Ggplot Cheat Sheet. However, all required graphics for this course can be constructed using qplot().

The qplot() function has a couple of basic components:

  • data = specifies the data set in which the variables exist.
  • x = specifies the variable for the x-axis.
  • y = if needed, specifies the variable for the y-axis.
  • geom = determines the way the data is displayed on the graphic.

Additional components allow you to group similar observations based on another variable. The idea is to “map” variables to attributes of the graphic:

  • color = specifies which variable in the data determines the exterior color of the objects.
  • fill = specifies which variable in the data determines the fill-color of the objects plotted.
  • size = specifies which variable in the data determines the size of the objects plotted.
  • shape = specifies which variable in the data determines the shape of the objects plotted.

In addition to the components above, we can “add” labels using the labs() function. As the examples below illustrate, labels are defined by the features set in the graphic command itself (x, y, color, etc.). We now discuss various ways of combining these settings to create common graphics.

Categorical Variable: Bar Chart

A bar chart is the simplest (and often best) method for summarizing the distribution of a categorical variable. The key steps to making a bar chart include:

  1. Place the variable you want to summarize on the x-axis.
  2. Set geom = "bar".
  3. Note: nothing goes on the y-axis.

For example, we can summarize the number of vehicles with each type of transmission using the following code.

qplot(data = mtcars,
      x = am,
      geom = "bar") +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "Frequency")

We remove the label on the x-axis because the value of the variable makes it clear what is being summarized.

Multiple Categorical Variables: Bar Charts

If you have multiple categorical variables, consider using additional aesthetics to group variables. We will consider a bar chart summarizing the type of engine and the type of transmission for each vehicle. First, we clean up the way that the variable vs is coded:

mtcars = mtcars %>%
  mutate(vs = recode(vs,
                     `0` = "V Engine",
                     `1` = "Straight Engine"))

Now, we construct the graphic using the following steps:

  1. Place primary variable of interest on x-axis.
  2. Use fill = to set the secondary variable.
  3. Use geom = "bar".

Again, we remove the labels of both the fill and the x variables because the values are self-evident.

qplot(data = mtcars,
      x = am,
      fill = vs,
      geom = "bar") +
  labs(x = "",
       fill = "",
       y = "Frequency")

Quantitative Variable: Histogram

When looking at the distribution of a single variable, a histogram is a reasonable choice, especially for medium-sized datasets.

  1. Set the variable to summarize on the x-axis.
  2. Choose geom = "histogram".
  3. Set the binwidth = option to a reasonable size (how large do you want each bin to be). This changes for each problem and is a matter of opinion on what gives a reasonable looking graphic.
qplot(data = mtcars,
      x = mpg,
      geom = "histogram",
      binwidth = 1) +
  labs(x = "Miles per Gallon",
       y = "Frequency")

In this graphic, we set the binwidth to be 1. We could also have considered a larger binwidth of 3, for example:

qplot(data = mtcars,
      x = mpg,
      geom = "histogram",
      binwidth = 3) +
  labs(x = "Miles per Gallon",
       y = "Frequency")

If you exclude the binwidth = option, it will choose a value for you:

qplot(data = mtcars,
      x = mpg,
      geom = "histogram") +
  labs(x = "Miles per Gallon",
       y = "Frequency")
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Quantitative Variable: Density

A density plot is like a smooth histogram; this works best with larger datasets.

  1. Set the variable to summarize on the x-axis.
  2. Choose geom = "density"
qplot(data = mtcars,
      x = mpg,
      geom = "density") +
  labs(x = "Miles per Gallon",
       y = "Density")

The y-axis on this graphic is not directly interpretable; essentially they have been chosen such that the area under the curve is equal to 1. Our primary interest here is that larger values mean the values on the x-axis are more likely.

Quantitative Variable: Boxplot

A boxplot gives a quick summary of location and spread for a numeric variable.

  1. Set the variable to summarize on the y-axis.
  2. Set the x-axis to be empty: "".
  3. Choose geom = "boxplot"
qplot(data = mtcars,
      y = mpg,
      x = "",
      geom = "boxplot") +
  labs(y = "Miles per Gallon",
       x = "")

Quantitative Variable Across Groups: Boxplots

If we are examining the distribution of a quantitative variable across various groups formed by a categorical variable, we can use side-by-side graphics, such as boxplots.

  1. Set the variable to be summarized on the y-axis.
  2. Place the grouping variable on the x-axis.
  3. Set geom = "boxplot".
qplot(data = mtcars,
      y = mpg,
      x = am,
      geom = "boxplot") +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "Miles per Gallon")

Quantitative Variable Across Groups: Violin Plots

Boxplots summarize the center and spread of the data, but the shape is lost. Violin plots generalize boxplots by incorporating the shape.

  1. Set the variable to be summarized on the y-axis.
  2. Place the grouping variable on the x-axis.
  3. Set geom = "violin".
qplot(data = mtcars,
      y = mpg,
      x = am,
      geom = "violin") +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "Miles per Gallon")

Quantitative Variable Across Groups: Individual Value Plots

When we have a small sample, boxplots are inappropriate because they hide the raw data and present an overly confident summary. Instead, we prefer to place the raw values on the plot.

  1. Set the variable to be summarized on the y-axis.
  2. Place the grouping variable on the x-axis.
  3. Set geom = "point".
qplot(data = mtcars,
      y = mpg,
      x = am,
      geom = "point") +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "Miles per Gallon")

If it looks too overwhelming because you have just enough points that they overlap, you can “jitter” the points:

  1. Set the variable to be summarized on the y-axis.
  2. Place the grouping variable on the x-axis.
  3. Set geom = "jitter".
  4. Set height = 0 to prevent the data from being jittered vertically.
qplot(data = mtcars,
      y = mpg,
      x = am,
      geom = "jitter",
      height = 0) +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "Miles per Gallon")

Quantitative Variable Across Multiple Groups

Boxplots, Violin Plots, and Individual Value Plots can all be extended to include additional other groups by adding aesthetics. For example, we can construct a side-by-side boxplot which also fills according to the engine type.

  1. Set variable to be summarized on the y-axis.
  2. Set the primary grouping variable on the x-axis.
  3. Set the secondary grouping variable as an aesthetic (fill =, color =, etc.)
  4. Set geom = "boxplot" for example.
qplot(data = mtcars,
      y = mpg,
      x = am,
      fill = vs,
      geom = "boxplot") +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "Miles per Gallon",
       fill = "")

Two Quantitative Variables: Scatterplot

When examining the relationship between two quantitative variables, we can use a scatterplot.

  1. Set the response (variable to be explained or predicted) on the y-axis.
  2. Set the predictor (the “given” information) on the x-axis.
  3. Set geom = "point".
qplot(data = mtcars,
      y = mpg,
      x = wt,
      geom = "point") +
  labs(y = "Miles per Gallon",
       x = "Weight (1000 lbs)")

Adding Features to Scatterplots

Just as with other plots, we can add additional features to a scatterplot. In general, the following two guiding principles help when thinking about these additional aesthetics:

  • Groups are best distinguished using color or shape.
  • Quantitative variables are captured using color or size.

The following graphic examines the relationship between the fuel efficiency (MPG) of a vehicle and its weight, while also considering the transmission type of the vehicle. Since “transimission type” is categorical, we use the color to separate these groups.

  1. Set the response (variable to be explained or predicted) on the y-axis.
  2. Set the predictor (the “given” information) on the x-axis.
  3. Set the grouping variable using color =.
  4. Set geom = "point".
qplot(data = mtcars,
      y = mpg,
      x = wt,
      color = am,
      geom = "point") +
  labs(y = "Miles per Gallon",
       x = "Weight (1000 lbs)",
       color = "")

We could also have used shape of the points instead.

qplot(data = mtcars,
      y = mpg,
      x = wt,
      shape = am,
      geom = "point") +
  labs(y = "Miles per Gallon",
       x = "Weight (1000 lbs)",
       shape = "")

If we want to look at the relationship between the fuel efficiency (MPG) of a vehicle and its weight, while also considering its horsepower, we do things a bit differently. Since “horsepower” is quantitative, we can use color or size to distinguish between various values. Both versions are shown below.

  1. Set the response (variable to be explained or predicted) on the y-axis.
  2. Set the predictor (the “given” information) on the x-axis.
  3. Set the secondary predictor using color =.
  4. Set geom = "point".
qplot(data = mtcars,
      y = mpg,
      x = wt,
      color = hp,
      geom = "point") +
  labs(y = "Miles per Gallon",
       x = "Weight (1000 lbs)",
       color = "Horsepower")

qplot(data = mtcars,
      y = mpg,
      x = wt,
      size = hp,
      geom = "point") +
  labs(y = "Miles per Gallon",
       x = "Weight (1000 lbs)",
       size = "Horsepower")

Common Distributions in R

R has lots of distributions built-in. A list of popular ones, along with their parameterizations is given in the following table.

Distribution Function Form of Density
Beta dbeta \(\frac{\Gamma(a+b)}{\Gamma(a)\Gamma(b)} x^{a-1}(1-x)^{b-1}\)
Binomial dbinom \(\binom{n}{x}p^x(1-p)^{n-x}\)
Cauchy dcauchy \(\frac{1}{\pi s (1 + ((x - l)/s)^2)}\)
Chi-Squared dchisq \(\frac{1}{2^{n/2}\Gamma(n/2)} x^{(n/2) - 1}e^{-x/2}\)
Exponential dexp \(\lambda e^{-\lambda x}\)
F df \(\frac{\Gamma\left(\left(n_1+n_2\right)/2\right)}{\Gamma\left(n_1/2\right) \Gamma\left(n_2/2\right)} \left(\frac{n_1}{n_2}\right)^{n_1/2} x^{(n_1/2) - 1} \left(1 + \left(\frac{n_1}{n_2}\right)x\right)^{(n_1+n_2)/2}\)
Gamma dgamma \(\frac{1}{s^a \Gamma(a)} x^{a-1}e^{-(x/s)}\)
Geometric dgeom \(p (1-p)^x\)
Hypergeometric dhyper \(\frac{\binom{m}{x} \binom{n}{k-x}}{\binom{m+n}{k}}\)
Log-Normal dlnorm \(\frac{1}{\sigma x \sqrt{2\pi}} e^{-\left(\frac{(\log(x) - \mu)^2}{2\sigma^2}\right)}\)
Multinomial dmultinom \(\frac{\left(\sum_{j=1}^K x_j\right)!}{\prod_{j=1}^K x_j!} \prod_{j=1}^K p_j x_j\)
Negative Binomial dnbinom \(\frac{\Gamma(x+n)}{\Gamma(n) x!} p^n (1-p)^x\)
Normal dnorm \(\frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}} e^{-\left(\frac{(x-\mu)^2}{2\sigma^2}\right)}\)
Poisson dpois \(\frac{\lambda^x e^{-\lambda}}{x!}\)
Student’s t dt \(\frac{\Gamma((n+1)/2)}{\sqrt{n\pi} \Gamma(n/2)} \left(1 + \frac{x^2}{n}\right)^{-((n+1)/2)}\)
Uniform dunif \(\frac{1}{\text{max} - \text{min}}\)
Weibull dweibull \(\left(\frac{a}{b}\right)\left(\frac{x}{b}\right)^{a-1} e^{-(x/b)^a}\)

If you use any of these functions, be sure to check that the parameterization you want matches that in R. Not all programs parameterize distributions the same way (for example, R parameterizes the Normal distribution in terms of the standard deviation, while we often write it in terms of the variance). For each distribution, there are actually four functions of interest:

  • dxxx: computes the value of the density function. For continuous random variables, this is not typically helpful. For discrete random variables, this is the probability of being equal to the value.
  • pxxx: the CDF, giving the probability of being less than or equal to a value.
  • qxxx: the inverse CDF; so, given a probability, give the corresponding quantile.
  • rxxx: randomly generate a sample from this distribution.

For example, pnorm(3, mean = 0, sd = 2) will return \(Pr(Z \leq 3)\) where \(Z \sim N(0, 4)\). Each function has a different set of arguments based on the parameters of the corresponding distribution.

Simple Operations with Functions

For very simple problems, we can make use of basic functionality in R. These could also be accomplished in other computing environments such as Maple or Matlab if you prefer.

Writing Functions

Writing functions in R could be its own text. Indeed, several have been written on the subject. We will just give the basic components of writing a function in R. This is helpful if the distribution you want to work with is not specified in R already.

For example, suppose we want to define the triangular distribution in R, which has the following density function

\[ f(x) = \begin{cases} \frac{2 (x - a)}{(b - a)(\mu - a)} & a \leq x \leq \mu \\ \frac{2(b - x)}{(b - a)(b - \mu)} & \mu < x \leq b \end{cases} \qquad a \leq x \leq b \]

which has parameters \(a \in \mathbb{R}\), \(b > a\), and \(a < \mu < b\). If we wanted to write a function called dtriangular that returned the value of this density function, we could code it as follows:

dtriangular <- function(x, params){
  a <- params[1]
  mu <- params[2]
  b <- params[3]
  
  f <- ifelse(x <= mu,
              (2 * (x - a)) / ((b - a) * (mu - a)),
              (2 * (b - x)) / ((b - a) * (b - mu)))
  
  f <- ifelse((x < a) | (x > b), 0, f)
  
  f
}

While this function is relatively simple, it illustrates several key ideas about writing functions in R.

  1. Functions are created by a call to function(). We use function_name <- function() to create a function called function_name.
  2. Inside function() are the list of arguments to the function (sometimes called parameters, but we do not want to confuse that with parameters of a distribution). In the above example, there are two arguments, x, the value at which we want to compute the density and params a vector of values giving the parameters. So, arguments can be a mix of data types.
  3. The body of the function is defined inside curly braces {}. Any R code is allowed within the function.
  4. The function returns the last object stated inside; in this case, f is called as the last thing; so, it returns the value of f.
  5. Functions work like math functions; they take inputs and return outputs. They do not alter the original inputs.
  6. Functions, when possible, should be vectorized. This is a subtle point. Notice that the value x passed to the function does not need to be a single number, it could be a vector of numbers and the function would still work. This allows for more efficiency. Generally, this is not too hard to do, but every once in a while, it requires clever thinking. In our case, we used ifelse() in order to check the bounds for each value in the vector x.

As an aside, also notice that inside the function, we indexed the params vector. Indexing in R begins with 1.

We could now call our function with the following:

dtriangular(3, params = c(0, 3, 6))
[1] 0.3333333
dtriangular(c(0.25, 0.5, 0.75), params = c(0, 0.5, 1))
[1] 1 2 1

Integrating a Function

Once we have defined a function, we can integrate it. For example, consider the triangular distribution defined in the previous section. Suppose, we have \(X \sim tri(0, 0.5, 1)\) and we are interested in \(Pr(X < 0.25)\); then, this is computed by

\[\int_{0}^{0.25} f(x) dx\]

This is simple to do by hand, but we can implement this in R using our function from before. Integration will be performed using the integrate() function, which has the following key arguments:

  • f: the name of the function to integrate.
  • lower: the lower bound of integration (-Inf is allowed).
  • upper: the upper bound of integration (Inf is allowed).

There are other arguments, but these are the most important. In addition, any arguments that must be specified for the function being integrated should also be included.

Note: for integration, it is important that the function was written to handle a vector.

integrate(dtriangular, lower = 0, upper = 0.25,
          params = c(0, 0.5, 1))
0.125 with absolute error < 1.4e-15

Here, we pass the arguments params = c(0, 0.5, 1) to R in addition to the bounds of integration.

Finding a Root

Here, we illustrate a simple case of finding the root of a function; that is, we are solving a single nonlinear equation. Suppose we want to find the value of \(q\) such that \(1 = f(q)\) where \(f\) is the density function for a triangular distribution with \(a = 0, \mu = 0.5, b = 1\). Root finding assumes you are solving an equation that is equal to 0. So, we rewrite this as

\[0 = g(q) = f(q) - 1\]

Therefore, we write a function zerofct for which we would want to set it equal to 0 to solve our problem.

zerofct <- function(x){
  1 - dtriangular(x, params = c(0, 0.5, 1))
}

Now, we can use the uniroot() function to actually obtain the root. The key arguments are

  • f: the name of the function to solve.
  • lower: the lower bound to an interval that contains our root.
  • upper: the upper bound to an interval that contains our root.

Note that for this method to work, we must have an idea of a region in which the root occurs. Here, it is logical that a root would occur between the lower end of the support and the mode of the distribution \(\mu\). Therefore, we search between \(0, 0.5\).

uniroot(zerofct, lower = 0, upper = 0.5)
$root
[1] 0.25

$f.root
[1] 0

$iter
[1] 1

$init.it
[1] NA

$estim.prec
[1] 0.25

Here, we see that our root is obtained at uniroot(zerofct, lower = 0, upper = 0.5)$root. Of course, you might say “isn’t there another root?” The answer is yes. This is a limitation of numerical methods; you cannot necessarily find all roots of a function. For a better treatment of this subject, consider the course MA332 Introduction to Computational Science.

For solving a system of nonlinear equations, look at the Optimization section.

Optimization

Consider once again our triangular distribution. In particular, suppose \(X \sim tri(0, 0.5, 1)\). Now, from the form of the distribution, we know the mode (value at which the density is maximized) is given at 0.5 — the value of the parameter \(\mu\). Let’s pretend for a moment we did not know that. Instead, we simply know that a mode exists somewhere in the support.

Finding the mode is equivalent to maximizing the density function. In optimization, most problems are framed in terms of minimization; however, switching is easy. If you want to find the value of \(x\) which maximizes \(g(x)\), that is equivalent to finding the value of \(x\) which minimizes \(-g(x)\). So, we first write a function that switches the sign:

minfct <- function(x){
  -dtriangular(x, params = c(0, 0.5, 1))
}

Now, we use the function optim() to perform the optimization. There are a couple of key arguments:

  • par: the first argument is the initial value for the parameter (our best guess).
  • fn: the name of the function to optimize.
  • method: most cases, you can accept the default; if you are doing one-dimensional optimization, we need to specify method = "Brent".
  • lower: only needed if method = "Brent"; specifies the lower bound of an interval containing the optimal point.
  • upper: only needed if method = "Brent"; specifies the upper bound of an interval containing the optimal point.

Since we are doing one-dimensional optimization (only looking over a single argument of the function), we will use method = "Brent", and we will also set an interval; we believe the mode is in the support \(0, 1\).

optim(par = 0.25, fn = minfct, method = "Brent", lower = 0, upper = 1)
$par
[1] 0.5

$value
[1] -2

$counts
function gradient 
      NA       NA 

$convergence
[1] 0

$message
NULL

In this example, we started with a best guess of 0.25, and it resulted in finding the optimal point of 0.5 (as we should hope since we knew that to be the answer). Notice that we need to ensure that convergence actually occurred (the convergence value is 0).

One application of optimization is solving a system of nonlinear equations. For example, let \(X \sim N\left(\mu, \sigma^2\right)\). Suppose we want to find the values of \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\) such that

\[ \begin{aligned} 0.05 &= Pr(X < 0) = \int_{-\infty}^{0} f(x \mid \mu, \sigma) dx \\ 0.05 &= Pr(X > 100) = \int_{100}^{\infty} f(x \mid \mu, \sigma) dx \end{aligned} \]

where we have written the density function to express that it is a function of the parameters \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\). There is not a function in R for solving a system of nonlinear equations. However, consider the function

\[g(x \mid \mu, \sigma) = \left[0.05 - \int_{-\infty}^{0} f(x \mid \mu, \sigma)dx\right]^2 + \left[0.05 - \int_{100}^{\infty} f(x \mid \mu, \sigma) dx\right]^2.\]

Observe that the function \(g\) is non-negative; therefore, it is minimized when the system of equations above is met. So, solving the system of equations is equivalent to minimizing \(g\) as a function of the parameters \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\). First, we write the function \(g\) into R:

gfct <- function(params){
  mu <- params[1]
  sigma <- params[2]
  
  f1 <- pnorm(0, mean = mu, sd = sigma)
  f2 <- 1 - pnorm(100, mean = mu, sd = sigma)
  
  (0.05 - f1)^2 + (0.05 - f2)^2
}

Now, we use optim() to perform the minimization where our initial values consider setting the mean to be right between 0 and 100, and taking the standard deviation to be 15.

optim(par = c(50, 15), fn = gfct)
$par
[1] 50.00026 30.39766

$value
[1] 3.579684e-12

$counts
function gradient 
      61       NA 

$convergence
[1] 0

$message
NULL

We find that taking \(\mu = 50\) and \(\sigma \approx 30.4\) results in a solution to the system.

Frequently Asked Questions

There are some things students run into a lot. Here are some common situations.

I just want to look at my dataset; how?

The easiest way is to go to the “Environment” tab in RStudio and double-click on the name of the dataset. It will open a spread-sheet like interface for looking at your dataset.

My variable name has spaces and R does not like it!

Variable names which have spaces in them need to be wrapped in back ticks. Technically, all variable names can be done this way, but it is a requirement when the variable name has spaces. For example, the following is allowed:

mtcars = mtcars %>%
  mutate(`Miles Per Gallon` = mpg)

Why does my code block not have a green arrow?

A code block should be completely separate from surrounding text. So, be sure there is a blank line both before the code block and after it. Usually, this fixes the problem.

How can I make a caption for my graphic?

In your code chunk, include the fig.cap option. For example, a code chunk might look like the following:

```{r, fig.cap="Relationship between fuel efficiency and the horsepower of a vehicle."}
qplot(data = mtcars
      x = hp
      y = mpg) +
  labs(x = "Horse Power",
       y = "Miles per Gallon")
```

This block would produce the following image (notice caption below image):

Relationship between fuel efficiency and the horsepower of a vehicle.

R is not treating my “grouping” variable correctly!

Generally, this happens when your “grouping” variable is a number instead of a phrase. For example, in the mtcars dataset, the variable cyl takes values 4, 6, or 8. However, R does not know that these values represent groups instead of actual values. In order to get the program to recognize it as a group, rewrite the variable using factor():

mtcars = mtcars %>%
  mutate(cyl = factor(cyl))

Now, cyl will be treated as a grouping variable. This needs to be done only once and will work for all subsequent graphics and models constructed.

Note: you could also recode the variable manually if you wanted to:

mtcars = mtcars %>%
  mutate(cyl = recode(cyl,
                      `4` = "4 Cylinder",
                      `6` = "6 Cylinder",
                      `8` = "8 Cylinder"))

The choice is yours.
